info.remarks: Sent to B.M. 1937, by Mrs. Carson. In a letter 28.5.38 she says she has now interviewed the workman who found it, and his statement is that he found it "about 8 years ago (i.e. c. 1930) in the bed of the R. Meon where the Titchfield-Stubbington road crosses it " when "excavating for the foundations of a small road-bridge"; he "came upon it about 4 feet below the surface of the river bed, a few feet from the downstream side of the bridge." This bridge is in Titchfield Parish, the bridge being in fact at the end of Bridge Street, Titchfield, which continues across it as the road to Stubbington.

info.description: Dimensions: L 310mm; Wbl 58.9; Ws 29.6; Bs 28.3; DS 280; Wt. 431.9 g[;]Typology: fillets defining midrib marginally bowed in sympathy with blade outline: lozenge midrib with hints of emphasised ridge which becomes real rib on circular section socket, termination level with fillets; sub-rect. fillet bases; sl. angle in bl. edge close to its base gives suggestion of an obtuse 'barb' or offset; small penetration of blade by socket.[;]Manufacture: socket neat on reverse side but with irregular small step/groove on obverse - marking cg. fl. line; peg holes probably cast; good concave e. bev.; small perf. close to s.m. not obviously modern.[;]Condition: edge mainly good; tip blunted - sim. colour to rest; dent assoc. with diag.scratching on socket rev. - pres. modern.

info.other: 3 cross section drawings of spearhead and photo of cast on reverse.[;]Socket and blade appear to be separate items that were riveted together with 2 large round rivets on either side of socket a little ways above socket blade stop.[;]Blade has a wide rounded, central midrib (socket extension?) that narrows toward tip.  Between midrib and edge on either side is a sharp furrow that look like they create a diamond shape to the blade between midrib and edge. Blade has a large, transverse fracture approximately halfway down blade that likely broke the original in two pieces.  At blade stop on socket, blade is wider, then narrows to a still relatively wide tip, almost an elongated bell-shape.[;]Edge is well intact on cast, surface appears to have minor pock marking.
